liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Red Cross has resumed patient escorts to the Gaza border after it temporarily halted operations after its convoy came under fire earlier this week, the head of its Gaza office said on Thursday, describing the incident as "deeply alarming" and calling for safety guarantees. "The ICRC was targeted the day before yesterday, and that is unacceptable," William Schomburg, the head of the ICRC delegation in Gaza told Reuters. "We took a pause yesterday," he added, saying it had resumed patient transfers from Gaza City to the Egypt border crossing on Thursday. Asked in the same interview if the ICRC had any staff fatalities, he said a colleague had been missing for weeks, without elaborating. Mr Schomburg also voiced alarm about overcrowding in cramped shelters where hundreds of thousands of Gazans have fled to, especially as many thousands more flee south, hoping to avoid the brunt of Israel's ground invasion. "It's a particularly difficult image in my mind, seeing thousands upon thousands of individuals with a look of total fear on their faces, carrying few of their possessions, some waving white flags as they moved on foot to seek greater safety and protection," he told Reuters. "Unless there is a reduction in the hostilities and if humanitarian aid is able to enter at a greater rate than it currently is, then the lives of civilians will become increasingly pressurised as resources become ever more scarce," he said. The International Committee of the Red Cross, a neutral organisation based in Geneva, has escorted patients and freed hostages out of Gaza since the conflict began more than a month ago and is protected under international humanitarian law.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Red Cross resumes escorting Gaza patients after convoy shooting

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Israel has described newly released videos showing two hostages held in Gaza as a "sign of life," but called them part of their captors' campaign of "psychological warfare". The armed wing of the Palestinian group Islamic Jihad in Gaza released a video on Thursday (local time) showing an elderly woman and a young boy, identified as Hanna Katzir, 77, and Yagil Jacob, 12, who were among about 240 hostages seized by militant gunmen who attacked Israel on October 7. The ABC cannot confirm what conditions these videos were filmed under and has chosen not to share them. The group said it was prepared to release the two for humanitarian and medical reasons once appropriate conditions were met but did not give further details. In the videos, Hanna and Yagil speak in Hebrew, blaming Israel's Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu for causing the current conflict and urging him to withdraw from Gaza. The two also talk about how they miss their home and their loved ones. "I love all of you and hope I'll be able to see you next week," Hanna said. Yagil added, "I hope that I will return as soon as possible, because as time goes by I am in greater danger." Reuters/ABC
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: New videos of two Israeli hostages described as 'psychological warfare'

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has skirted officially confirming that there would be daily four-hour humanitarian pauses in Gaza and instead suggested any pauses would be scattered. The US White House had said earlier that Israel agreed to pause military operations in parts of north Gaza to allow people to flee along two humanitarian corridors, which could also be used for the release of hostages. In an interview with Fox News, Mr Netanyahu said the fighting with Hamas would continue when asked if there would be a "stoppage". "No. The fighting continues against the Hamas enemy, the Hamas terrorists, but in specific locations for a given period of a few hours here or a few hours there, we want to facilitate the safe passage of civilians away from the zone of fight and we're doing that." Israeli officials earlier spoke more generally of measures that appeared to correspond to arrangements already in place. In recent days, Israel has allowed civilians safe passage along the main Gaza route south for three or four hours each day. The White House's comments suggested a second route would be opened. Reporting with Reuters
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Israeli PM remains vague on four-hour humanitarian pause

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The US Treasury Department says a ransomware attack on China's largest bank, the Industrial and Commercial Bank of China (ICBC), disrupted some trades in the US Treasury market overnight, but the impact on the market is unclear. Earlier, the Financial Times reported that the US Securities Industry and Financial Markets Association (SIFMA) told members that ICBC had been hit by ransomware, preventing the US Treasury market from settling trades on behalf of other market players. "We are aware of the cybersecurity issue and are in regular contact with key financial sector participants, in addition to federal regulators. We continue to monitor the situation," a Treasury spokesperson told Reuters in a response to a question about the FT report. ICBC, China's largest commercial lender by assets, has begun to restore services, while the US Treasury appears to be functioning normally, according to data from the London Stock Exchange Group (LSEG). Scott Skrym from Curvature Securities in the US said the event had a "limited impact" on the market.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: China's largest bank hit by ransomware attack, disrupts US Treasury market trades

children.content: The US Treasury Department says a ransomware attack on China's largest bank, the
Industrial and Commercial Bank of China (ICBC), disrupted some trades in the US Treasury market overnight, but the impact on the market is unclear.

Earlier, the Financial Times reported that the US Securities Industry and Financial Markets Association (SIFMA) told members that ICBC had been hit by ransomware, preventing the US Treasury market from settling trades on behalf of other market players.

"We are aware of the cybersecurity issue and are in regular contact with key financial sector participants, in addition to federal regulators. We continue to monitor the situation," a Treasury spokesperson told Reuters in a response to a question about the FT report.

ICBC, China's largest commercial lender by assets, has begun to restore services, while the US Treasury appears to be functioning normally, according to data from the London Stock Exchange Group (LSEG).
Scott Skrym from Curvature Securities in the US said the event had a "limited impact" on the market.
